FILE TINDER — SCREEN-BY-SCREEN RATINGS
=======================================

Methodology: Each screen is rated on UI Design (layout, visual hierarchy,
consistency, responsiveness) and Features (completeness, depth, edge cases,
user control). Grades: A (excellent), B (good with minor gaps), C (functional
but needs work), D (significant problems), F (broken/missing).


==============================================================================
SCREEN 1: LAUNCHER (FileTinderLauncher — main.cpp)
==============================================================================

UI Design Grade:  B+
Feature Grade:    B

LAYOUT & VISUAL HIERARCHY
  + Title "FILE TINDER" is prominent (28px bold, accent blue) — immediately
    establishes brand identity and draws the eye.
  + Logical top-to-bottom flow: title → description → folder picker → recent
    folders → mode buttons → tools → keyboard hints.
  + Mode buttons are large (180x70px), color-coded (green/purple/blue), and
    side-by-side — easy to scan and distinguish at a glance.
  + Path indicator changes from gray "(none selected)" to green with a
    green-tinted background when a folder is chosen — clear visual feedback
    that something is selected.
  + Resume session indicator has its own distinctive styled box (blue-tinted
    background, blue border, blue text) — clearly visible without being
    intrusive.
  - Tools row (Clear Session, Undo History, Light Theme, Diagnostics) uses
    identical gray styling for all four buttons — no visual differentiation
    between destructive (Clear Session) and informational (Diagnostics)
    actions. Clear Session should be red-tinted or at least visually distinct.
  - Keyboard hints label at the bottom is a single long string crammed into
    10px font — hard to parse. Would benefit from grouping by mode or using
    a table layout.
  - No visual separator between the folder selection area and the mode
    buttons — the sections run together.

RESPONSIVENESS & SIZING
  + Minimum size (550x450) is reasonable for the content.
  + DPI scaling applied via ui::scaling::scaled() on relevant dimensions.
  - Recent folders list has a fixed maxHeight of 80px scaled — could clip
    on small screens or with long folder paths.
  - Mode buttons use fixed minimumSize — they don't grow proportionally
    on large screens, leaving whitespace on ultrawide monitors.

FEATURES
  + Folder picker with native OS dialog — familiar and reliable.
  + Recent folders list with click-to-select and middle-click-to-remove —
    efficient for power users. The middle-click interaction is documented
    in the label text.
  + Resumable session detection: checks for saved progress and shows a
    count of files already sorted — prevents accidental restarts.
  + Pre-session statistics dashboard: shows file count, total size,
    type breakdown (Images/Videos/Audio/Documents/Archives/Other), and
    subfolder listing — gives users a clear picture before committing.
  + Database auto-cleanup of sessions older than 30 days — good hygiene.
  + Dark/light theme toggle persisted in QSettings — preference survives
    restarts.
  + Stale session cleanup on startup — prevents database bloat.
  - skip_stats_on_next_launch_ is declared but never read in a meaningful
    way outside mode switch — dead state variable.
  - Theme toggle is only available here — cannot change theme while in a
    sorting mode without returning to the launcher.
  - No keyboard shortcut to launch modes (e.g., 1 for Basic, 2 for
    Advanced, 3 for AI) — requires mouse for mode selection.
  - No drag-and-drop folder selection — must use the file dialog.
  - No indication of which mode was last used.
  - No way to compare modes or see a brief description of each mode's
    workflow before launching.

EDGE CASES
  + Handles non-existent folders gracefully (warning dialog when clicking
    a stale recent folder).
  + Empty folder check before launching any mode.
  + Database initialization failure shows a critical error.
  - No handling of permission-denied folders (user selects a folder they
    can't read — error only appears later during scan).


==============================================================================
SCREEN 2: PRE-SESSION STATISTICS DASHBOARD (show_pre_session_stats)
==============================================================================

UI Design Grade:  B+
Feature Grade:    B-

LAYOUT & VISUAL HIERARCHY
  + Clean card-like layout with a header showing the folder path in bold
    blue — immediately contextualizes the data.
  + Summary line uses bold/middot formatting for quick scanning: "X files ·
    Y total · Z subfolders".
  + Type breakdown uses color-coded labels (blue for images, red for videos,
    purple for audio, green for documents, orange for archives, gray for
    other) — each type is visually distinct and recognizable.
  + Breakdown panel has a contrasting dark background (#34495e) with rounded
    corners — clearly delineated as a distinct information group.
  + Subfolder section has its own panel with a "Subfolders (N)" header and
    a scrollable list — good separation of concerns.
  + "Start Sorting" button is large, green, bold, and right-aligned — clear
    primary action.
  - Cancel button has no distinct styling — uses default. Should have at
    least a border or subtle background.
  - Types with zero count are silently hidden (via add_row returning early)
    — this is correct behavior but means a user with only images sees a
    single line, which could look sparse.

FEATURES
  + File count and total size calculation with human-readable formatting
    (B/KB/MB/GB).
  + MIME-based type detection using QMimeDatabase — more accurate than
    extension-only matching.
  + Progress dialog for large directories (>200 files) — prevents the
    appearance of freezing.
  + Subfolder preview (up to 10 shown, "...and N more" for overflow) —
    gives context without overwhelming.
  - No filtering or drill-down — cannot click a type to pre-filter the
    session to only that type.
  - No per-type size breakdown (e.g., "Images: 45 files, 2.3 GB") — only
    counts are shown, not cumulative sizes per type.
  - No indication of the deepest nested path or total directory depth.
  - No file size distribution info (e.g., "Largest file: 4.2 GB").
  - No preview of the first few files — just statistics.


==============================================================================
SCREEN 3: BASIC MODE — SORTING SCREEN (StandaloneFileTinderDialog)
==============================================================================

UI Design Grade:  B-
Feature Grade:    B+

LAYOUT & VISUAL HIERARCHY
  + Classic card-based layout with file preview in the center — mirrors
    the Tinder metaphor effectively.
  + DELETE and KEEP buttons are large (18px bold), color-coded (red/green),
    side-by-side — the most important actions are the most prominent.
  + Skip button is full-width but thinner and orange — clearly secondary.
  + Progress bar with percentage text and filter info — always visible,
    always informative.
  + Stats bar uses color-coded counts (green Keep, red Delete, orange Skip,
    blue Move) — scannable at a glance.
  + Duplicate warning ("!") button appears only when relevant — not always
    present, reducing clutter.
  + Bottom bar arranges utility actions (Undo, Preview, Reset) on the left
    and navigation (Search, File List, Finish Review) on the right — logical
    grouping by purpose.
  - File type icons are TEXT-BASED ("[IMG]", "[VID]", "[ZIP]") in monospace
    at 48px — functional but ugly. The app has SVG icon resources that are
    not being used. This is the most visible visual debt in the entire app.
  - The file card has a flat dark background (#2c3e50) with a thin border —
    it doesn't feel like a "card" that can be swiped. No shadow, no depth,
    no skeuomorphic hint of the card metaphor.
  - Swipe animation is a simple opacity fade — minimal. No horizontal slide,
    no rotation, no momentum. Compared to actual Tinder's physics-based card
    animations, this feels static.
  - The file info label doubles as a clickable element (double-click to open)
    but has no visual affordance beyond a pointer cursor — users won't
    discover this unless they read the tooltip.
  - Size badge is displayed separately below the info label in large orange
    text — redundant with the size already shown in the info label. The
    two pieces of information compete for attention.

RESPONSIVENESS & SIZING
  + Debounced resize events (150ms timer) for preview updates — prevents
    stutter during continuous resizing.
  + Preview uses QImageReader::setScaledSize() for efficient loading —
    avoids decoding full-resolution images into memory.
  + Text preview truncated to 1500 chars — prevents layout explosion.
  - The file card stretches to fill available space (stretch factor 1) but
    the image preview inside doesn't scale proportionally on very tall
    windows — could leave large blank areas above/below the image.

FEATURES
  + Full keyboard-driven workflow: Right=Keep, Left=Delete, Down=Skip,
    Z=Undo, F=File List, P=Preview toggle, Enter=Finish, Ctrl+F=Search.
  + Undo system with unlimited stack depth — every action is reversible.
  + Session persistence: decisions saved to SQLite on every action (crash
    safety) and restored on relaunch.
  + Comprehensive file filtering: 8 filter types (All, Images, Videos,
    Audio, Documents, Archives, Other, Folders Only) plus Custom extension
    filter.
  + 4-way sorting: by Name, Size, Type, Date Modified, each with
    Ascending/Descending toggle.
  + Include Folders toggle to optionally sort directories alongside files.
  + File List window (F key) for multi-select batch assignment.
  + Image Preview window (separate popup with zoom/fit/navigation).
  + Duplicate detection badge with drill-down to DuplicateDetectionWindow.
  + Search box for quick file lookup.
  + Context menu on file info: Open File, Open Containing Folder.
  + Reset Progress with confirmation dialog.
  + Mode switching preserves session state.
  - No "move to folder" action in Basic mode — only Keep/Delete/Skip. To
    move files, users must switch to Advanced mode. This limits Basic mode's
    utility for users who want simple sorting into 2-3 folders.
  - File preview toggle (P key) is all-or-nothing — cannot resize the
    preview area. On small screens, the preview dominates; on large screens,
    it's small relative to the card.
  - No batch operations — files must be reviewed one at a time (except via
    the File List window).
  - No auto-advance after a configurable delay (for rapid sorting).
  - Filter change with existing decisions prompts a reset — aggressive.
    Should offer "apply filter to remaining only" as an option.


==============================================================================
SCREEN 4: ADVANCED MODE — SORTING SCREEN (AdvancedFileTinderDialog)
==============================================================================

UI Design Grade:  A-
Feature Grade:    A-

LAYOUT & VISUAL HIERARCHY
  + The grid of folder buttons IS the screen — it dominates the layout as
    it should. The primary action (clicking a folder) is the most spatially
    prominent element.
  + Folder buttons use consistent sizing within each mode (compact: 120x32,
    expanded: 180x36) — creates a clean, uniform grid.
  + Visual differentiation between folder types:
    - Default folders: dark blue-gray with subtle border
    - External folders: purple-tinted — immediately identifiable
    - Virtual/new folders: dashed orange border — suggests "will be created"
    - Custom-colored folders: user-assigned colors with darker backgrounds
    - Root folder: bold blue border — clearly special
    - Focused/selected: bright blue with thicker border — unambiguous
  + File info panel is a compact horizontal bar below the grid — shows
    [ICON] Name | Size | Type | Date with an 80x80 inline image preview.
    Efficient use of vertical space.
  + Quick Access panel as a horizontal scrollable list — visible but not
    intrusive. Numbered slots (1-0) match keyboard shortcuts.
  + Action buttons (Delete, Keep, Skip, Undo) in a horizontal row at the
    bottom — secondary to folder clicking but always accessible.
  + Grid toolbar (Rows, Compact/Expanded, Full Paths, Width, A-Z, #, Save,
    Load, Reset, Presets) — comprehensive but dense. Every control is small
    (10px font, max 70px width) to avoid dominating the screen.
  - Grid toolbar has 11 controls in a single row — overwhelming on first
    use. Would benefit from grouping (Display | Sort | Config) or hiding
    behind an expandable panel.
  - Quick Access item names are truncated to 14 characters — too aggressive
    for many folder names. "Vacation_Photos" becomes "Vacation_Phot…" which
    loses meaning.
  - The "+" add folder button (28x28, green) at the end of the grid can be
    hard to spot when there are many folders — it blends into the grid.
  - No visual indicator of which file is "current" beyond the info panel.
    In a dense grid, the user's eye is on the folders, not the info bar.
    A stronger visual cue for the current file would help.

FEATURES
  + Folder tree model with add/remove/rename/reposition — full CRUD.
  + Grid configurations: save/load/reset — users can preserve folder
    layouts across sessions.
  + Template presets (Downloads Cleanup, Photo Organization, Development
    Project, Music Library, Document Archive) — excellent onboarding.
  + Drag-and-drop folder reposition within the grid — spatial memory.
  + Keyboard navigation via Tab (enter grid mode) → arrow keys (navigate) →
    Enter (assign) → Escape (exit grid mode) — fully accessible.
  + Color coding with 8 preset colors via right-click menu — visual
    categorization.
  + Context menu per folder: Move File Here, Add to Quick Access, Open
    Folder, Replace with..., Add Subfolder, Set Color, Remove from Tree.
  + Root folder click = Keep in place — intuitive mapping.
  + Quick Access: 10 slots (keys 1-0), add/remove/clear, middle-click
    removal, persisted to database.
  + Multi-folder selection via file dialog with ExtendedSelection — batch
    add existing folders.
  + External folder support with warning dialog — files can be moved
    outside the source directory.
  + Missing folder detection on session resume — alerts user if folders
    were deleted between sessions.
  + Assigned file counts shown on folder buttons — visual progress.
  + Grid sorting: alphabetical and by file count.
  + First-time onboarding prompt with usage instructions.
  - No folder search/filter — with 50+ folders, finding the right one
    requires scrolling. A search bar above the grid would help.
  - No undo for folder operations (add/remove/rename) — only file decisions
    are undoable.
  - No folder grouping or hierarchy visualization — all folders are flat
    siblings in the grid regardless of their actual directory structure.
    Subfolders appear at the same level as top-level folders.
  - No drag-and-drop from the file info panel to a folder — must click.
  - No confirmation when assigning a file to a folder — instant action.
    Good for speed, but risky for misclicks (mitigated by undo).


==============================================================================
SCREEN 5: AI MODE — SORTING SCREEN (AiFileTinderDialog)
==============================================================================

UI Design Grade:  A-
Feature Grade:    A

LAYOUT & VISUAL HIERARCHY
  + Extends Advanced mode's grid layout — users who learn Advanced mode
    already understand the spatial metaphor.
  + AI Setup and Re-run AI buttons inserted into the title bar — accessible
    but not dominant. The primary interaction is still the grid.
  + AI Suggestions panel is a separate horizontal list below the quick
    access — visually distinct with blue-tinted background and bold blue
    text. Items show rank numbers ("1: Documents", "2: Images").
  + AI log panel (QTextBrowser) shows real-time progress during analysis:
    processing status, batch progress, API responses — transparency into
    the AI's decision-making.
  + Semi-mode highlights suggested folders in the grid — visual connection
    between AI output and user action.
  - The AI Suggestions panel and Quick Access panel look similar (both are
    horizontal scrollable lists with similar styling) — could be confused.
    The AI suggestions use slightly different colors (#1a3a5c vs #34495e)
    but the difference is subtle.
  - No visual indicator of AI confidence per file in the grid view — the
    confidence scores are in the AI log but not surfaced in the primary
    interaction area.
  + [FIXED] Re-run AI button is disabled until first setup — tooltip added
    explaining WHY it's disabled.

FEATURES
  + Dual sorting modes: Auto (AI decides everything, user reviews) and
    Semi (AI suggests top-N folders per file, user confirms).
  + 4 category handling modes: Keep Existing, Generate New, Synthesize,
    Keep + Generate — covers all use cases.
  + Configurable subcategory depth (1-3 levels).
  + Optional folder purpose description — gives AI context for better
    categorization ("This is my Downloads folder" leads to different
    categories than "This is my music production folder").
  + Confidence threshold filtering — hide low-confidence suggestions.
  + Smart rate limiting with per-provider defaults and 429 backoff.
  + Multi-provider support (OpenAI, Anthropic, Gemini, Mistral, Groq,
    OpenRouter, Ollama, LM Studio, Custom) with preset endpoints and models.
  + Model fetching from provider APIs — auto-populates available models.
  + Cost estimation with per-model pricing — transparent before committing.
  + Batch processing (50 files/request) — efficient API usage.
  + Taxonomy-aware prompting — the AI understands that "Serum.dll" is a VST
    plugin, not just a DLL file.
  + Category review dialog — after AI generates new categories, users can
    edit/add/remove them before they're created in the grid.
  + Correction tracking — when users override AI suggestions in Semi mode,
    the feedback is incorporated into subsequent prompts.
  + Re-categorization option — re-analyze already-sorted files against
    changed folder structure.
  - API keys stored in plaintext SQLite — security concern. Should use OS
    keychain (Keychain on macOS, Credential Manager on Windows, Secret
    Service on Linux).
  - No offline/mock mode — cannot test or develop without an API connection
    or local LLM running.
  + [FIXED] File progress bar added during AI analysis — shows overall
    progress percentage.
  - Correction tracking is session-only — lost on restart. Persistent
    corrections would improve the AI over time.
  + [FIXED] Reasoning label added showing WHY the AI chose a particular
    folder — not just the folder name and confidence score.


